0. 1️⃣ Problems Kubernetes Solves (Before vs After)
	   		Before Kubernetes, teams building microservices had to build or buy solutions for: 
				Problem						Before Kubernetes					With Kubernetes
			Load balancing				L4/L7 proxies						Native Services
			Service discovery			Eureka / Consul						DNS‑based
			Scaling						Custom autoscaling code				HPA
			Deployments					Blue‑green tools					Rolling updates
			Environment drift			Config per VM						ConfigMaps & Secrets
			Infra dependency			Tight coupling						Cloud‑agnostic

	   		Kubernetes standardizes these concerns at the platform level.
   
   2️⃣ Microservices Design Patterns Kubernetes Replaces (or Internalizes)
		Kubernetes doesn’t “kill” microservices patterns — it moves them from application code into infrastructure.
		1. Service Discovery Pattern (Mostly Replaced)
			Before Kubernetes: Netflix Eureka, Consul, Zookeeper, Custom discovery libraries
			Each service had to: Register itself, Discover others, Handle failures.
			With Kubernetes: Native DNS-based service discovery
			Every Service gets: service-name.namespace.svc.cluster.local	
				✅ No registration code
				✅ No discovery client
				✅ No heartbeat logic
			Status: ✅ Replaced by Kubernetes Service + DNS
			
		2. Client‑Side Load Balancing (Replaced)
			Before Kubernetes: Ribbon, Custom round‑robin logic, Application SDKs for load balancing
			With Kubernetes: kube‑proxy handles load balancing, Service distributes traffic to Pods
			✅ App doesn’t choose instances
			✅ No LB libraries inside code
			Status: ✅ Moved to Kubernetes networking layer

		3. Self‑Healing Pattern (Replaced)
			Before Kubernetes: Supervisord, custom watchdogs, cron restart jobs
			With Kubernetes: Liveness probes, Readiness probes, Controllers continuously reconcile desired state
			Status: ✅ Fully replaced
	

