5. kubectl create deployment nginx-demo --image=nginx
	This command means Create a Deployment named nginx-demo that runs the nginx container image.
	✅ What exactly gets created?
		1️⃣ Deployment (main object)
		2️⃣ ReplicaSet (created automatically)
		3️⃣ Pod (runs the container)
	✅ This command roughly translates to the following YAML. Kubernetes creates this for you automatically, You didn’t have to write YAML
		apiVersion: apps/v1
		kind: Deployment
		metadata:
		  name: nginx-demo
		spec:
		  replicas: 1
		  selector:
		    matchLabels:
		      app: nginx-demo
		  template:
		    metadata:
		      labels:
		        app: nginx-demo
		    spec:
		      containers:
		      - name: nginx
		        image: nginx


✅ How to verify what was created
	kubectl get deployments							// Check the Deployment
	kubectl get pods								// Check the Pod
    kubectl describe deployment nginx-demo			// Describe for details

✅ Can you access nginx now?
	No — not yet. Why?
		Pods are internal
		No Service is created
	To expose it:  kubectl expose deployment nginx-demo --type=NodePort --port=80
		the command means Create a Service for the nginx-demo Deployment and expose it on every node’s IP using a high port, forwarding traffic to container port 80.
		This command creates a Service object:
			apiVersion: v1
			kind: Service
			metadata:
			  name: nginx-demo
			spec:
			  type: NodePort
			  selector:
			    app: nginx-demo
			  ports:
			  - port: 80
			    targetPort: 80
			    nodePort: 300XX

		Traffic flow:
			Client → NodeIP:NodePort → Service → Pod → Nginx

		Example access: http://<node-ip>:30080
		
		✅	Why NodePort Is Not Recommended in Production ?
			1️⃣ No Load Balancer: Kubernetes does not distribute traffic across nodes for NodePort.
			2️⃣ Direct Node Exposure (Security Risk)
			3️⃣ No TLS / HTTPS by Default
			4️⃣ Cloud‑native networking has evolved (2026). In 2026, production Kubernetes expects: Ingress, Service Mesh, Gateway API, mTLS, Policy‑driven networking.
				 NodePort is a legacy exposure method.
				 Kubernetes Ingress vs Gateway API:
					Ingress = legacy, simple, app‑focused
					Gateway API = modern, extensible, platform‑grade
	
		✅ What Production Uses INSTEAD (2026)
			Option 1: Ingress (Most Common)	
					  Client → HTTPS → Ingress → Service (ClusterIP) → Pod
		
			Option 2: LoadBalancer Service
					  kubectl expose deployment nginx-demo --type=LoadBalancer --port=80
		
			Option 3: Gateway API (Modern Standard – 2026)
					  The successor to Ingress:
						Stronger API guarantees
						Better multi‑team control
						Native traffic policies
						Designed for platform engineering
					This is now the strategic direction of Kubernetes networking.
		
		✅	When NodePort IS Acceptable in 2026
				Still valid for: 
				  Local environments: Minikube, Kind, K3s on laptop.
				  Debugging: Temporary access, Incident response.
				  On‑prem.
	
✅ When should you use kubectl create deployment?
	Learning Kubernetes, Quick tests, PoCs, Interviews & demos
	❌ Not ideal for: Production setups, GitOps workflows, Complex configs (resources, env vars, probes).

✅ For Production use below command
	 kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml


5. GKE steps to follow to deploy a microservice
        1.  gcloud services enable container.googleapis.com artifactregistry.googleapis.com 
        2.  set environment variables like PROJECT_ID, REGION, ZONE, CLUSTER, REPO, APP. 
        		gcloud config set project $PROJECT_ID 
        		gcloud config set compute/zone $ZONE 
        3.  Create GKE cluster 
        		gcloud container clusters create %CLUSTER% --num-nodes=2 --machine-type=e2-medium --zone %ZONE%
        4.  Get kubeconfig credentials 
        		gcloud container clusters get-credentials %CLUSTERS% --zone %ZONE%
        		kubectl get nodes
        5.  Create Artifact Registry repo: 
        		gcloud artifacts repositories create %REPO% --repository-format=docker --location=%REGION% 
        6.  Configure Docker auth: 
        		gcloud auth configure-docker %REGION%-docker.pkg.dev 
        7.  create image format and build and push image
        		set IMAGE_V1="%REGION%-docker.pkg.dev/%PROJECT_ID%/%REPO%/%APP%:v1" 
        		docker build -t %IMAGE_V1% . 
        		docker push %IMAGE_V1% 
        8.  Deploy microservice to GKE 
        		1. deployment.yaml - How your application runs
					A Deployment defines how your application should run inside the cluster. It Ensures the desired number of pods is always running, Restarts failed pods,
					Supports rolling updates and rollbacks. Kubernetes keeps 3 pods running at all times. It answers questions like:
						Which container image to run?
						How many copies (pods) should run?
						How to update the app without downtime?
						What if a pod crashes?
				
        		2. service.yaml	- How users access your application
					Pods have Dynamic IPs, Short lifetimes, So you cannot rely on pod IPs to reach your app.
					A Service.yaml provides a stable network endpoint and Load balancing across pods.
					It Exposes your application inside or outside the cluster. 
					Routes traffic to healthy pods. Load-balances requests automatically

        		3. hpa.yaml - How your app scales automatically
					Traffic is not constant:
						Peak hours → high CPU
						Off hours → waste resources
					HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) automatically adjusts pod count and Monitors metrics (CPU/memory).

				✅ Real-world analogy
					Think of a restaurant:
						Deployment → Kitchen staff (how many cooks, replacement if someone leaves)
						Service → Reception counter (customers don’t go directly to kitchen)
						HPA → Hiring/removing cooks based on crowd


					
		
